th a `$` inside? The guideline says \\\"never use $ in test class or file names,\\\" but I wonder if that applies to the string itself. It's a class binary name for the service loader, so using `IbmVendorKerberosErrorRunner.class.getName()` could load the parent version. I'm also curious if the child loader will behave differently when finding classes.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating class creation**\\n\\nI’m thinking about whether I can create a class in the com.ibm package using javax.tools during testing. It seems that's not allowed and may be unsupported natively. But, is it really necessary? Maybe the test fails because the class initializes beforehand, so perhaps a child loader can help solve this. I still need to figure out if the current test is directly using sun. Adding a child loader for testing might be the way to go.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating class loading**\\n\\nI’m considering how class loading works, specifically with build directories like build/classes/java/test and the Kafka jar. It seems that in native environments, there is no dynamic class path, which could lead to unsupported issues. The existing setup only uses the temp directory and relies on the `java.class.path`. If a property is missing, it might be unsupported, but including the whole classpath could lead to order issues when loading classes. I want to ensure the child-first loader finds dependencies properly.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_8FvKZOsimlwvYg2BBbIC1ILz|fc_01c70654245d360c016a0f41025cb4819daaf60c24da9eaeca", "name": "edit", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/org.apache.kafka/kafka-clients/4.2.0/src/test/java/org_apache_kafka/kafka_clients/OrgApacheKafkaCommonSecurityKerberosKerberosErrorTest.java", "edits": [{"oldText": "import org.apache.kafka.common.security.kerberos.KerberosError;\nimport org.junit.jupiter.api.Test;\n\nimport sun.security.krb5.KrbException;\n\nimport static org.assertj.core.api.Assertions.assertThat